node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.text: We're back with another episode of AD Visits, and today, we're taking you to Hudson Yards to see the home of fashion designer @brian_atwood and husband @drjakedeutsch. With photography on every wall and incredible city views 64 stories above Manhattan, explore their high-rise artistic aerie. Cover photo by @twilliamsphoto.

node.text:
A recurring note in this coastline oasis in Mexico is ceramic tile, produced in Guadalajara, in a bespoke palette of palmy greens, earthy browns, and ocean blues, inspired by the surrounding landscape. #AD100 designer @luislaplace used the tile to tie the rooms together: on walls in the bedrooms, baths, and kitchen; for tabletop surfaces; to enrobe the bar.

Explore more from our cover home at our bio link. Photo by @fernandomarroquint; styling by Mariana Estrada; design by @luislaplace; words by @danathomasparis.

node.text:
“We liken ourselves to a 19th-century guild,” says Katherine Newman of the Toronto-based firm she cofounded with architect Peter Cebulak in 1991. Because rather than specialize in a single field @katherinenewmandesign spans multiple disciplines, from architecture to interior design, construction management, and even landscaping. “We take on only five projects a year, but our body of work is very diverse,” says Newman of her lean and nimble methodology. “We have no stamped aesthetic and hire no junior designers. We see ourselves as editors.”

See one of those projects—a Georgian-style revival in Toronto—at our bio link. Photo by @virginmacdonald; design by @katherinenewmandesign; words by Katie Chang.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 12, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
The result of presenting #AD100 talent Giancarlo Valle (@studiogiancarlovalle) with this blank canvas in NYC is a tapestry of tantalizing rooms that unfolds to dynamic and delightful effect—moment to moment, mood to mood. In some cases, the starting point was the palette, whether the dining room’s allover aubergine or the primary bedroom’s enveloping navy. “The clients had strong opinions about color,” Valle notes. “Together we pushed it even further, building a story around these elemental bursts.”

Tour the brilliant home at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; styling by @colinking; design by @studiogiancarlovalle; words by @samuelcochran.

node.text:
“It’s a boys world over here, so while the design is elegant and has moments of luxury, it’s still meant to be lived in,” designer Vanessa Alexander (@alexanderdesignbuild) says of this home in Malibu. The faint casbah vibes of the youngest son’s bedroom have less to do with the Moroccan poufs and pillows covered in global textiles than with a custom corner sofa, clearly designed for leisure.

Step inside the beautiful spaces at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; styling by @rowelosangeles; design by @alexanderdesignbuild; words by @leilanimarielabong.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 12, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
“There is so much joy in the South of France,” recalls #AD100 designer @indiamahdavi, who is based in Paris. There is an artistic legacy that was inescapable to a visually minded child growing up in the French Riviera. Raoul Dufy, Marc Chagall, and Henri Matisse all lived in Mahdavi’s hometown of Venice at one point, and Matisse’s masterwork, the Chapelle du Rosaire, is there. “I’ve always been influenced by Matisse and how he approaches light through his vision of color,” she says. “It’s a quest for light, in fact.”

See her work her magic on a friend's home at our bio link. Photo by Vincent Leroux; design by @indiamahdavi; words by @samedford.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 11, 2021. May be an image of sky and skyscraper.

node.text:
On September 11, 2001, architect Santiago Calatrava (@calatravaofficial) was in Athens designing the 2004 Olympic Stadium. At that time, Calatrava had already created some of the world’s most renowned structures. But on that day, he was like the rest of us, horrified at what he saw developing on the television screen. “From my hotel [in Athens] I could see the Parthenon,” Calatrava notes. “That too was destroyed but built back in a spectacular way. I knew the same could happen in New York.” 

In honor of the 20th anniversary of 9/11, we talked to the designer of the Oculus about the transformation of lower Manhattan over the last two decades.

Read more at our bio link. Words by @iamnickmafi.

node.text:
The 5,000-square-foot home is in an exclusive pocket of Preston Hollow in North Dallas that has a cadre of modernist homes. “We painted the brick walls white and kept the roof brown as a nod to the original cedar shingles,” says architect and designer @eddiemaestri. “Black-and-white cabana drapes and a valance were added to dress up the entry and give it a Palm Springs vibe.”

Visit our bio link to explore the whole home. Photo by @nathanschroderphoto; styled by @jennyoconnorstudio; design by @maestristudio; words by @whatpaolasees.

node.text:
One of the most exciting aspects of design is that it changes constantly. The points of view found in the shapes, colors, and styles of our favorite spaces are ever evolving, as are the voices that bring those spaces to life. Coast to coast, a fresh crop of creative talents is writing the next chapter in great interior design—and they're names you need to know.

Meet them at our bio link. node.text:
Architects delight in constraints. A sheer cliff, an enormous boulder, some mature trees—every challenge is an opportunity, every obstacle a eureka moment. Enlisted by a creative couple to update their Manhattan town house, #AD100 talent Giancarlo Valle (@studiogiancarlovalle) found no such conditions to navigate. Recently constructed and lacking in character, the five-story downtown dwelling was just box rooms, white walls, and soulless developer details—an aesthetic vacuum, for all intents and purposes. And so, deprived of any natural jumping-off points, Valle created his own. “A project like this, it’s a blank canvas,” he reflects. “You almost have to create the game.”

Tour the brilliant home he designed at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; styling by @colinking; design by @studiogiancarlovalle; words by @samuelcochran.

node.text:
Architecturally speaking, the landmark Wilshire Boulevard Temple (@wilshireboulevardtemple), home to the oldest Jewish congregation in Los Angeles, is a tough act to follow. Built in 1929 and designed by architect Abram M. Edelman in a hybrid of Byzantine and Romanesque styles, the magnificent domed synagogue has all the exotic glamour of the great movie palaces of the era. OMA (@oma.eu @omanewyork), the Rotterdam-based Office for Metropolitan Architecture, won the WBT commission for a new structure, the Audrey Irmas Pavilion, on the congregation’s Erika J. Glazer Family Campus.

Step inside the new pavilion at our bio link. Photo by @jasonorear; design by @shohei_shigematsu; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 09, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
Somewhere on the Floridian coast, one sophisticated Palm Beach residence possesses a particularly compelling mise-en-scène: A 6,000-square-foot waterfront location, paired with a façade that recalls an uber chic super yacht on terra firma. The international-style pied-à-terre—conceptualized and brought to life by architect and interior designer Gerard Beekman of Gramatan Architecture and Design and @livingstonbuilders_inc—serves as a much-needed winter reprieve for a Chicago-based couple and their twin daughters, who jaunt down on weekends from New York City.

See the yacht-inspired home at our bio link. Photo by @sargentphotos; design by Gerard Beekman and @livingstonbuilders_inc; words by @katiekiefner.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on September 09, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and living room.

node.text:
Designer @brigetteromanek has translated her philosophy of livable luxury into a bright, breezy line of home furnishings for retailer Mitchell Gold + Bob Williams (@mgbwhome). “I like furniture that’s practical—the right pitch, the right level of comfort—but there has to be more. There has to be an element of playfulness and joy,” says the #AD100 designer, whose LA collection blends rounded silhouettes and taut forms for a distinctly upbeat personality, more timeless than trendy.

Get an exclusive first look at her collection at our bio link. Photo by @williamwaldronphoto; design by @brigetteromanek; words by @mayer.rus.
